	<theorem xml:id="theorem-pythagorean">
		<title>Pythagorean Theorem</title>
		<statement><p>For a triangle containing a right angle <me>a^2+b^2=c^2</me> where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are the lengths of the sides adjacent to the right angle.</p></statement>
	</theorem>

	<p>In a later section we will develop a version of this statement for triangles without a right angle.</p>

	<theorem xml:id="theorem-herons-formula">
		<title>Heron's Formula</title>
		<statement><p>The area of a triangle can be calculated using the three sides. <me>A = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</me> where <m>s=\frac{1}{2}(a+b+c)</m>.</p></statement>
	</theorem>

	<example xml:id="example-heron-triangle">
		<statement><p>Calculate the area of the triangles in <xref ref="figure-exercise-triangle-area" />.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>According to Heron's formula for the triangle on the left
			<md>
				<mrow>s &amp; = \frac{1}{2}(5.98+8.19+10.9)</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = 12.535.</mrow>
				<mrow>\text{Area} &amp; = \sqrt{12.535(12.535-5.98)(12.535-8.19)(12.535-10.9)}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = 24.16.</mrow>
			</md>
			For the triangle on the right
			<md>
				<mrow>s &amp; = \frac{1}{2}(5.98+8.19+2.87)</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = 8.515.</mrow>
				<mrow>\text{Area} &amp; = \sqrt{8.515(8.515-5.98)(8.515-8.19)(8.515-2.87)}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = 6.3.</mrow>
			</md>
		</p></solution>
	</example>

